      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πρῶτον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or, according to B ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "א",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πρώτως",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Lobeck, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ad Phryn.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " p. 311 f.), because here the Christians, in consequence of the predominant Gentile-Christian element, asserted themselves for the first time not as a sect of Judaism, but as an independent community. There is nothing to support the view that the name was at first a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "title of ridicule",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (de Wette, Baumgarten, after Wetstein and older interpreters). The conjecture of Baur, that the origin of the name was referred to Antioch, because that was the first Gentile city in which there were Christians (Zeller also mistrusts the account before us), cannot be justified by the Latin form of the word (see “Wetstein, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
